				<li>Create your (Dream Smile)</li>
			</ul>

			<p>
				<b>Filling Procedure</b><br>
				There are two types of fillings for dental cavities.  A Direct Filling is generally completed in one office visit and an Indirect Filling in two office visits.
			</p>	
			<p>
				<b>Direct Fillings for Dental Cavities</b><br>
				TLC Dental first addresses a dental cavity by thoroughly examining a tooth to determine the location, nature, and extent of the cavity.  If it is suitable for a direct filling we then remove the decayed material, clean the affected area, prepare a liner or base if needed, properly shape the area, and emplace the filling.
			</p>	
			<p>
				<b>Indirect Fillings for Dental Cavities</b><br>
				There are two types of indirect fillings.  An inlay is a filling within the cusps (bumps) on the chewing surface of a tooth.  An onlay covers a more extensive area than an inlay and is often called a partial crown.<br>
			</p>
			<p>
				The initial steps in an indirect filling procedure are the same as those for a direct filling procedure save for the immediate emplacement of the filling.  In lieu of that, an exact measurement and mold (impression) of the area and a precise color match with your natural teeth are made for a specialized laboratory that prepares a high quality permanent filling. A temporary filling is then emplaced pending the completion, emplacement, and polishing of its successor.<br>
			</p>
			<p>
				In both direct and indirect fillings, TLC takes exceptional care to assure that your fillings provide for not only healthy teeth but also attractive teeth.<br>
			</p>											
			<p>
				<b>Gentle Comfort</b><br>
				In the preparation and emplacement of your fillings, you will enjoy the comfort of  our signature “Gentle Dentistry.”
			</p>			
			<p>
				<b>Filling Composition</b><br>
				TLC offers fillings of different composition that we thoroughly review with you to determine which one best realizes your Dream Smile.<br>
			</p>
			<p>
				Amalgam Fillings  are the least expensive and one of he strongest and longest lasting fillings. The FDA, ADA, and World Health Organization find that the very low levels of mercury in amalgam fillings hold no health risks<br>
			</p>
			<p>
				Gold Fillings are made to our exact specifications by a highly specialized laboratory.  They are non-corrosive and are the longest lasting of fillings.  They are well tolerated by gum tissue and their appearance is preferred by some patients.<br>
			</p>
			<p>
				Composite Resin Fillings gain additional support from bonding and can be used for several restorative purposes beyond fillings.  And they can be custom made to match the color of your natural teeth.<br>
			<p>
				Porcelain Fillings are made to our exact specifications by a highly specialized laboratory.  They wonderfully match the color of your teeth, are resistant to stains, and are very long lasting.<br>
			</p>			
			<p>
				<b>Filling Durability</b><br>
				The durability of a tooth filling, just like that of a normal tooth, is largely dependent on good dental hygiene and regular dental checkups.  With proper care, fillings may last for many years.
			</p>
